04722nam a22006735i 9781503632462DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222022cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021051935  a97815036324627 a10.1515/97815036324622doi  a(DE-B1597)627960  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aBF697.5.S65bT46 2022 4aBF697.5.S65bT46 2022 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a155.2223/eng/202111091 aThompson, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTwilight of the Self :bThe Decline of the Individual in Late Capitalism /cMichael Thompson. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (348 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tpart i: our steely encasement -- t1. The Rise of Cybernetic Society: The Patterned World and the Fate of the Individual -- t2. Social Domination, Social Systems, and the Constitution of the Self -- t3. The Reification Problem and the Normative Entanglement Hypothesis -- tpart II: an anatomy of heteronomy -- t4. Alienation: From Autonomy to Moral Atrophy -- t5. Reconsidering False Consciousness: An Etiology of Defective Social Cognition -- t6. Cultivating Consent: Reification and the Web of Norms -- t7. The Withering of the Self and the Regression of the Ego -- tpart III: to the lighthouse -- t8. Autonomy as Critical Agency: Reconstructing the Democratic Self -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this new work, political theorist Michael J. Thompson argues that modern societies are witnessing a decline in one of the core building blocks of modernity: the autonomous self. Far from being an illusion of the Enlightenment, Thompson contends that the individual is a defining feature of the project to build a modern democratic culture and polity. One of the central reasons for its demise in recent decades has been the emergence of what he calls the "cybernetic society," a cohesive totalization of the social logics of the institutional spheres of economy, culture and polity. These logics have been progressively defined by the imperatives of economic growth and technical-administrative management of labor and consumption, routinizing patterns of life, practices, and consciousness throughout the culture. Evolving out of the neoliberal transformation of economy and society since the 1980s, the cybernetic society has transformed the ways that the individual is articulated in contemporary society. Thompson examines the various pathologies of the self and consciousness that result from this form of socialization—such as hyper-reification, alienated moral cognition, false consciousness, and the withered ego—in new ways to demonstrate the extent of deformation of modern selfhood. Only with a more robust, more socially embedded concept of autonomy as critical agency can we begin to reconstruct the principles of democratic individuality and community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aDemocracyxPhilosophy. 0aNeoliberalism. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aSelfxSocial aspects. 0aSocial historyy1970- 0aSocial historyy1970-. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aalienation.  aautonomy.  acapitalism.  acritical theory.  aideology.  aindividuality.  areification.  asocial cybernetics.  atechnology studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363246240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503632462423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503632462/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University 